ACCELERATOR. THE PULSE WIDTH WAS 1 NS, THE REPETITION

N.O.
+ +  CORRECTED BY S.MAEV
ERROR STRUCTURE IS GIVEN.
SAMPLE KEYWORD MOVED TO PROPER SUBENTRIES
.THE DATA WERE CORRECTED FOR THE VARIOUS TRANSMISSIONS
THROUGH THE SAMPLES TO THE MONITOR.
.THE DATA WERE FURTHER CORRECTED FOR SAMPLE-INDEPENDENT
BACKGROUND, MEASURED WITH AN EMPTY SAMPLE FRAME. THE
REMAINING TIME-INDEPENDENT BACKGROUND WAS DETERMINED
AT VERY LONG FLIGHT TIMES, 3.9 MICRO-S.
.CORRECTIONS WERE ALSO APPLIED FOR THE ISOTOPIC COMPO-
SITION AND IMPURITIES.
.THE DATA WERE ALSO CORRECTED FOR SAMPLE-SCATTERED NEU-
TRONS, STUDIED WITH THE GRAPHITE SAMPLE.
.FINALLY, THE DATA WERE CORRECTED FOR MULTIPLE SCATTER-
ING, NEUTRON SELF-SHIELDING, GAMMA-RAY SELF-SHIELDING,
AND DETECTOR EFFICIENCY.
BAF2. THE CAPTURE EVENTS WERE DETECTED BY THE
KARLSRUHE 4PI BARIUM FLUORIDE DETECTOR, WHICH CONSISTS
OF 42 HEXAGONAL AND PENTAGONAL CRYSTALS FORMING A
SPHERICAL SHELL OF BAF2 WITH 10 CM INNER RADIUS AND
15 CM THICKNESS. IT HAS AN ENERGY RESOLUTION OF 7
PERCENT AT 2.5 MEV, A TIME RESOLUTION OF 0.5 NS AND A
PEAK EFFICIENCY OF 90 PERCENT AT 1 MEV. CAPTURE EVENTS
ARE DETECTED WITH 95 PERCENT PROBABILITY. THE FLIGHT
PATH THROUGH THE DETECTOR WAS ALSO EVACUATED TO AVOID
AIR SCATTERING.
A LI-6 GLASS DETECTOR, LOCATED CLOSE TO THE
NEUTRON TARGET, WAS USED TO NORMALIZE THE SPECTRA TO
EQUAL NEUTRON FLUX.
TOTAL ERROR OF THE CROSS-SECTION AND THE CROSS-
SECTION RATIO TO GOLD, OBTAINED BY ADDING THE STATIS-
TICAL AND SYSTEMATIC ERRORS IN QUADRATURE.
INCLUDES 1.5 PERCENT GOLD STANDARD ERROR
FLIGHT PATH, RATIO                 0.1
NEUTRON FLUX, RATIO                0.2
SAMPLE MASS, TE-ISOTOPES           0.1
ISOTOPIC ENRICHMENT, TE-ISOTOPES   0.2
UNOBSERVED EVENTS, RATIO           0.6
MULTIPLE SCATTERING IN AU          0.3
MULTIPLE SCATTERING IN TE-122      0.3
MULTIPLE SCATTERING IN TE-123      0.2
MULTIPLE SCATTERING IN TE-124      0.3
MULTIPLE SCATTERING IN TE-125      0.3
MULTIPLE SCATTERING IN TE-126      0.7
TOTAL SYSTEMATIC UNCERTAINTIES
THE KARLSRUHE PULSED 3.7 MV VAN DE GRAAFF
ACCELERATOR. THE PULSE WIDTH WAS 1 NS, THE REPETITION
RATE WAS 250 KHZ, AND THE AVERAGE PROTON BEAM CURRENT
WAS 1.5 - 2 MICROAMPS.
NEUTRONS WERE PRODUCED BY BOMBARDING A METALLIC
LITHIUM TARGET, WITH A THICKNESS OF 1 MG/CM2 FOR A
MAXIMUM ENERGY LOSS OF 100 KEV. THE PROTON ENERGY WAS
IN THREE DIFFERENT RUNS ADJUSTED TO 10, 30 AND 100 KEV
ABOVE THE REACTION THRESHOLD OF 1.881 MEV.
.CONTINUOUS NEUTRON SPECTRA COVERING 10 - 70, 3 - 100
AND 3 - 200 KEV IN THE THREE RUNS. THE NEUTRON BEAM
WAS COLLIMATED TO 25 MM DIAMETER AT THE SAMPLE
POSITION. THE NEUTRON FLIGHT PATH WAS EVACUATED TO
AVOID AIR SCATTERING, USING STAINLESS STEEL TUBES WITH
20 MICRO-M KAPTON FOIL WINDOWS, LEAVING ONLY AN AIR
GAP OF 1 CM FOR THE SAMPLE.
THE NEUTRON ENERGIES WERE DETERMINED WITH TIME-
OF-FLIGHT TECHNIQUES, WITH A FLIGHT PATH OF 78 CM TO
THE SAMPLE.
IN-BEAM GAMMA-RAY SPECTROSCOPY.
THE STANDARD AU CAPTURE CROSS SECTION
AS A FUNCTION OF ENERGY
WAS TAKEN FROM MACKLIN, AND NORMALIZED BY A FACTOR OF
0.989 TO THE ABSOLUTE VALUE OF RATYNSKI AND KAEPPELER.
.A 1115.56 MG METAL GOLD SAMPLE, 10 MM IN DIAMETER AND
0.8 MM THICK, WAS USED FOR MEASURING THE NEUTRON FLUX.
.THE BACKGROUND WAS DETERMINED BY MEASUREMENTS WITHOUT
SAMPLE, AND WITH A 165.72 MG GRAPHITE SAMPLE, 10 MM IN
DIAMETER AND 1.3 MM THICK, FOR THE STUDY OF SCATTERING
EFFECTS.
.THE SAMPLES WERE MOUNTED IN A SAMPLE CHANGER. THEY
WERE CYCLICALLY MOVED TO THE MEASURING POSITION. THE
MEASURING TIMES OF ABOUT 10 MINUTES WAS CONTROLLED BY
A COMPUTER. THE TOTAL NUMBER OF CYCLES WERE 200 - 260
FOR EACH OF THE THREE RUNS.
.DATA TAKEN FROM MAIN REF.

TO GOLD.

RATIO TO GOLD.
